    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1726137153" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1726137153" />
    <a title="Horza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7496298-horza"><img alt="Horza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1419398349p2/7496298.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1726137153?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Horza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Horza" href="/user/show/7496298-horza">Horza</a>
      </span>

          added it



          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">occultists, mediciacs, yorkists and lancastrians, grecophobes</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1726137153" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5997254553960491451">I found this one more of a struggle than I was anticipating. <br/><br/>As a magical romp through an alternate 15th century with dragons, wizards, vampires and a sinister totalitarian Byzantine Empire pulling the strings, <i>The Dragon Waiting</i> has a lot going for it. JM Ford clearly had a lot of fun flipping and twisting historical events to fit his unique setting, and there&apos;s a lot of clever references for those who know their Medicis, Plantagenets and ancient dieties. Those aren&apos;t really my bag, so I found </span>
  <span id="freeText5997254553960491451" style="display:none">I found this one more of a struggle than I was anticipating. <br /><br />As a magical romp through an alternate 15th century with dragons, wizards, vampires and a sinister totalitarian Byzantine Empire pulling the strings, <i>The Dragon Waiting</i> has a lot going for it. JM Ford clearly had a lot of fun flipping and twisting historical events to fit his unique setting, and there's a lot of clever references for those who know their Medicis, Plantagenets and ancient dieties. Those aren't really my bag, so I found <a href="http://eblong.com/draconc/index.html" rel="nofollow noopener">Draco Concordans</a> quite handy.<br /><br />And that's sort of the nub: <i>Dragon</i> is brimming with historical in-jokes, structured chapters, and stylised, genre-hopping set-pieces, but it's all a little too much (or maybe too little). There's slightly too many extraneous details* and while some historical characters work well, they're encumbered by all the As-You-Know-Bob required both to familiarise non-15th century people and set up Ford's alternate setting. While his protagonist characters are interesting and subtly-written they sort of get squeezed off the page by all the rest of it. The emotional impact of their decisions and choices was there but it felt muted by the brevity of their introductions and the puzzle-box world they were hurtling through (it didn't help that they're all ridiculously hypercompetent, particularly in the realms of knifework and hand-to-hand combat).<br /><br />I don't want to be too hard on <i>The Dragon Waiting</i>, it's a crazy book, almost Eco-like at times but with a fast-paced thriller plotline and a pulpy take on magic, divinity and those wacky late middle ages royals. If that sounds up your alley, do what thou wilt.<br /><br /><br />*Every historical fiction/alternate history writer seems to fall into the trap of painfully working in some personage or detail hard won in their research. Ford is no different but he's positively restrained compared to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1530734370?book_show_action=false" rel="nofollow noopener">other dragon-focused historical fantasy writers I could mention</a><a></a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5997254553960491451" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

