    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1772369505" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1772369505" />
    <a title="Simon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41670-simon"><img alt="Simon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550537487p2/41670.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1772369505?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simon" href="/user/show/41670-simon">Simon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1772369505" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3250085675872653593">I honestly don&apos;t know how to review this book, it&apos;s that personal. In some respects I am the perfect audience for it --- it hits all of my sweet spots, including the Byzantine Empire, ancient religions and Richard III. That being said, if these are <i>not</i> areas of interest, indeed, obsession, I can&apos;t imagine what reading this must be like. Ford spends at least half the book setting up the gathering of his four central characters, but the two most interesting --- Hywel and the vampire Gregory --- ar</span>
  <span id="freeText3250085675872653593" style="display:none">I honestly don't know how to review this book, it's that personal. In some respects I am the perfect audience for it --- it hits all of my sweet spots, including the Byzantine Empire, ancient religions and Richard III. That being said, if these are <i>not</i> areas of interest, indeed, obsession, I can't imagine what reading this must be like. Ford spends at least half the book setting up the gathering of his four central characters, but the two most interesting --- Hywel and the vampire Gregory --- are barely sketched in, which is a shame because, you know, wizards and vampires. However, the four of them eventually get to England in time for the accession crisis of Richard III. And if it was nutty before, it goes full out in this section of the book. You <i>have</i> to both know a great deal about the daily minutiae of Richard's power grab <i>and</i> control yourself during scenes like the one where Edward V and his little brother Richard are teeny vampires, biting at Sir James Tyrrel when he comes to do the Historical Nasty. <br /><br />This is not to say that the book wasn't enjoyable, but it could have been three times as long and still not covered all of the territory Ford was aiming at --- although the guy managed to tuck in references to every single historical figure of the time. The problem is that some of them are so brief that the reader wants a lot more explanation, but nope. Ford whirls on.<br /><br />There are also some technical problems about this alternate universe. Alright, Julian the Apostate lives and prevents the rise of Christianity, but does anyone seriously think that Western Europeans in the late 15th century would still have been worshiping Ishtar or Minerva? And what's with the Christian names for the characters. Not for anything, but. However, these are very minor cavils. The larger issue with the book is its scope in comparison to its length. And there won't be a sequel unless some enterprising fan fiction writer has taken a whack.<br /><br />Recommended, but with a <i>lot</i> more reservations than usual.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3250085675872653593" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


